          <div class="definition-box">
            <p>Hamilton has attracted a growing Chinese-Canadian community in recent years, drawn by more affordable housing and proximity to Toronto. When marriages in this community break down, finding a Mandarin-speaking family lawyer who serves Hamilton is the first obstacle. Miao He (何淼) provides full Mandarin family law services to Hamilton clients — <strong>primarily by Zoom and phone, so the distance from Markham is not a barrier</strong>. Court appearances are handled by Miao He. LSO #83315K · China Bar Association Licensed.</p>
          </div>

          <h2>How Miao He Serves Hamilton Clients</h2>
          <p>Hamilton is approximately one hour from Miao He's Markham office — far enough that requiring in-person visits for every step would be impractical. The good news is that most family law work does not require the client to be physically present. Here is how the process works for Hamilton clients.</p>

          <h3>Zoom and Phone Consultations: Full Service Without the Drive</h3>
          <p>Initial consultations, document review, strategy discussions, Separation Agreement drafting and review, and ongoing case updates are all conducted by video or phone. Most Hamilton clients complete the bulk of their matter without visiting the office. When court appearances are required, Miao He attends on the client's behalf. For clients who prefer to meet in person, arrangements can be made.</p>

          <h3>Divorce and Separation: Getting Out Cleanly</h3>
          <p>Whether both spouses agree on all terms or are deeply in dispute, Miao He guides Hamilton clients through the full divorce and separation process. A Separation Agreement — resolving property, support, and parenting — can be drafted and finalized entirely by video, with documents signed electronically. Where matters cannot be resolved by agreement, Miao He litigates at the Superior Court of Justice — Family Court in Hamilton (55 Main Street West).</p>

          <h3>Spousal Support: Duration and Amount</h3>
          <p>Spousal support is one of the most misunderstood areas of Ontario family law. The amount and duration depend on the length of the marriage, each spouse's income, the roles each played during the relationship, and the economic consequences of the breakdown. The Spousal Support Advisory Guidelines provide a range — not a fixed formula — and there is real room for negotiation. Miao He advises Hamilton clients on realistic support ranges and negotiates or litigates to achieve an appropriate outcome.</p>

          <h3>Property Division: Hamilton Real Estate</h3>
          <p>Hamilton's property market has appreciated significantly over the past decade. The increase in value during the marriage is subject to Equalization — but pre-marital value, parental contributions, and gifts from third parties may be excluded. Miao He helps clients establish the correct valuation baseline and protect assets that should not be divided.</p>

          <h3>Child Custody and Cultural Considerations</h3>
          <p>Chinese-Canadian families in Hamilton face the same cultural custody considerations as GTA communities — Chinese-language schooling, grandparent involvement, travel to China. Miao He builds Parenting Plans that address these specifics in legally binding terms.</p>

          <div class="qa-block">
            <h3>Q: Can I handle my divorce by video without traveling to the lawyer's office?</h3>
            <p>A: Yes. Most of the work — consultations, document preparation, Separation Agreement drafting — can be done by Zoom or phone. Court appearances are handled by Miao He. Hamilton clients rarely need to visit the Markham office. Call 647-930-6688 to book a Zoom consultation.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-block">
            <h3>Q: Does spousal support depend on how long we were married?</h3>
            <p>A: Yes, among other factors. Length of marriage affects both the amount and duration of support. Longer marriages typically result in longer obligations. Miao He can advise on a realistic support range for your situation. Call 647-930-6688.</p>
          </div>

